article.description: Lisa Leslie had 20 points and nine rebounds as the two-time defending champion Los Angeles Sparks staved off elimination in the first round of the playoffs Saturday night with an 80-69 win over the Minnesota Lynx.
article.headline: Balance carries L.A. as Sparks even series
article.linkText: All even in L.A.: Sparks top Minnesota, force Game 3
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Lisa Leslie had 20 points and nine rebounds
as the two-time defending champion Los Angeles Sparks staved off
elimination in the first round of the playoffs Saturday night with
an 80-69 win over the Minnesota Lynx.

The Sparks bounced back from blowing a 21-point lead in a
stunning 74-72 loss to the Lynx on Thursday. The decisive third
game of the series will be played at Staples Center on Monday.

"I thought we put together some good runs and you have to
credit this Minnesota team because a lot of people think they would
be just happy to be here," Sparks coach Michael Cooper said. "But
they really believe they can win."

Forward DeLisha Milton added 17 points and 10 rebounds for Los
Angeles, who relied on a strong transition game and 34 points in
the paint.

"We were confident in ourselves because we knew the mistakes we
made in the first game were on our own behalf," Milton said. "On
Thursday, our experience didn't play its part. Tonight, we stayed
focused for 40 minutes."

Guard Katie Smith led the Lynx with 18 points and Tamika
Williams added 17 and seven rebounds.

Minnesota's only lead was two minutes in, when they were up 5-3.
The Lynx committed 24 turnovers.

"We didn't take care of the basketball," Lynx coach Suzie
McConnell Serio said. "And we didn't play with confidence early
on."

The Sparks led 36-25 at halftime, thanks to a balanced scoring
attack, that featured nine points each from Leslie, Milton and
Tamecka Dixon.

Los Angeles went on an 18-6 run in the first eight minutes of
the second half, taking a 54-32 lead.

Minnesota narrowed the Sparks' margin to 75-67 with 1:58 left on
Sheri Sam's runner in the lane but couldn't make another run
similar to Thursday.

"It was a good win for us, not a pretty win, but it was a game
that we had to win," Cooper said.
